[09:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Milan. So, I get this question a lot, but many people ask me, "What are the biggest challenges I face when I am doing a 3D scan?"'

[09:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And my big four would be limited time, weather conditions, overcrowding, and going into restricted spaces. Places like the Olympic Museum that I scanned were very very restricted. And sometimes it can be all four at the same'

[10:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'time, which is which can be pretty insane. Um so, actually in this video um is an interpolation of a daytime scan that I did and a nighttime scan of the Duomo uh'

[10:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'using hand tracking. It was a Leap Motion Controller where you\'re able to kind of go left or right and uh switch between the daytime and nighttime scans, which I thought was so cool. Um you can'

[10:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'see in the nighttime scan there\'s not a lot of people, but within the daytime scan you can see these crowds of people. So, depending on your use case, I find crowds not too much of a negative thing'

[10:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'as it\'s just truly showing the real experience of it all. Um especially within this interpolation, it\'s kind of cool to see the people disappear when you\'re going from daytime'

[11:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to nighttime. Though on the flip side of it, uh when I\'m at Burning Man scanning art installations, we can\'t scan people who are on top of the art or taking a'

[11:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'picture with the art. We need to be able to scan the art as it was truly made by the artist, that true digital twin of it all, especially when you want to relive that memory of being near the art in VR.'

[11:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Um scanning people within will just not I think it\'s distraction or will will kill the experience. Um but then in parallel um having stable weather has been crucial.'

[11:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Um I don\'t find myself scanning in the rain or when we\'re out there on the playa, there are just so many unpredictable dust storms. And the winds are pretty intense. And sometimes these'

[11:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'winds can actually destroy the art installation, which makes it even more important to try and scan the piece before something might happen to it. Um again, we\'re doing our best, but I mean again,'

[12:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like you want to try and scan the art as it was made by the artist, you know, that integrity of it all. So um but overall, I mean, I look at these challenges as all learning'

[12:18] [scene:talk]
