[30:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and at the center of it uh is a man uh wooden man that they eventually burn on the last night and art everywhere. Now, I\'ve been pho- photographing uh'

[30:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this place since 1998 and my goal has just been trying to capture the feeling of being here, that sort of scope, the wind, the sounds. And uh the first camera I took out there was a Hi8 640 by 480 size frame on tape'

[30:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'back in 1998. And uh then we got digital 720 1080 4K and now 8K. And as time went on the images became clearer but I was still'

[30:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pushing to get out that feeling of being there which uh which was is tough. Now Burning Man is a temporary city just so I can explain to you guys out in Nevada.'

[31:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Uh for me uh it\'s focused on being a city full of art. It\'s also built to disappear. So the only way you can go to Black Rock City which is the name of Burning Man City itself is to be at the right place and at the right time. A sort of'

[31:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'supertemporal city. Uh now Burning Man started in 1986 and over time it formed these 10 principles. Uh some of them like radical'

[31:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'self-reliance, leaving no trace, communal effort to just name a few. And there\'s [clears throat] one principle called immediacy. Uh you\'re meant to be there fully in the moment. Uh the the definition of the of uh'

[31:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'immediacy is the direct experience of the present moment. It encourages participants to engage fully with their surroundings, art, and fellow attendees creating a rich tapestry of interactions'

[31:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that are spontaneous and meaningful. This principle is a response to the distractions of normal life urging individuals to put down their devices and uh immerse themselves in the experience. Uh for a long time there was no connectivity out at Burning Man, no'

[32:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'signal, no phones and people loved that. They would just completely disconnect. The art they saw they would have to tell people about because it was gone after that. So capturing it uh'

[32:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'has always been a tension with this immediacy. I was usually the one of the few people out there with a camera at all. Um and to a lot of burners photographing the art, taking it home feels like a violation of that thing'

[32:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that makes it sacred. That it was temporary. And that you had to be present for it. And I I\'ve been sitting inside that tension uh for over like 20 years. But we all we all know what happened next. Everyone'

[32:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'out there has a phone and a camera, and you\'re going to see every art piece on social media uh during the week uploaded by satellite internet. And whatever immediacy used to mean, connectivity is a fact now. Phones'

[32:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with a camera are a fact. &gt;&gt; [clears throat] &gt;&gt; And honestly, I wish we had a little bit more immediacy now, although I can see that I\'m part of the problem, frankly. &gt;&gt; [laughter]'

[33:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; But along my journey, I spent a lot of time thinking about how can we bring immediacy into a digital space? Uh and I think we did achieve that digital immediacy in BRCVR. Uh BRCVR'

[33:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'uh as I realized my 2D documentaries were never quite getting me that feeling of being there totally. Um you can show someone the playa, but you can\'t put So, around 2018 2019, I started getting'

[33:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into VR. And then in 2020, COVID hit, shut down Burning Man, and through a long story, which I don\'t have time to get into here, a group of us built BRCVR, a virtual Burning Man experience on the'

[33:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Altspace platform. Um and it got a lot of closer to immediacy. You\'d walk around, see art, run into random people all over the world, and have fantastic conversations. Uh it felt like a cartoon version of'

[34:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Burning Man. Uh but it was a little still too low poly for me. But we managed. And then in 2023, um Altspace was shut down. And we'

[34:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'decided we had all these assets, all these things that we had for Burning Man. And so uh we decided to build our own platform from the ground up.'

[34:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Um but leaning more towards documentary and video and scanning. And we\'ve released that in this last year and it\'s called Burner Sphere. And we started to rethink'

[34:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what we wanted in a social VR platform and we read into as much of the real as we could. We set out to let someone who\'s never been on the playa walk into it, an immersive explorable'

[34:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'documentary built in Unity. And it talks to lesson of this whole talk. People don\'t want a record of Burning Man, they want to stand inside it. That moment you give them the space to walk through instead of a frame to look at, the'

[35:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'community and the stories will come back with it. Because you\'re not preserving the art, you\'re preserving the place where the art happened. So we went out to Burning Man and shot in virtual formats. 180 3D, 360, photogrammetry,'

[35:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then last year we started adding in uh Gaussian splats cuz that\'s that\'s the ultimate experience for us. So so we decided to go out and shoot.'

